DRY. No repetition.

Production-ready code only. No TODOs, placeholders, leftovers, or “later”.

Extract shared utils, hooks, flows, and templates when there is clear reuse.

Do not create README or documentation files unless explicitly requested.

If changes to instructions or architecture are needed, propose them before writing code.

Do not disable pylint. Fix all pylint issues.

TypeScript: never use `any`. Always use the most specific correct type.

Do not use `require`. Use static imports. Use `require` only to resolve unavoidable circular dependencies.

Do not import solely to re-export. Avoid re-exports.

Index files may only re-export modules. Never write logic in index files.

Do not rename variables during destructuring unless there is a real naming collision in the same scope.

Do not run or attempt to execute applications. Only produce code and indicate when it is ready to test.

TypeScript: never use the 'as type/interface'.

Do not declare variables or files with underscore examples: const _DEV_ or _tests_

File must to not have more then 200 lines, in order to maintain readability and easy to refactor.

If project is written in typescript/javascript and when you need to create a file name it must be named as camelCase, for example thisIsNewFile.ts/js. if you tackle a file name that is not following that note that to the user.